<font color="#FF0000">THOUGHTS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jul  3 21:58:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Linley,<br>
     I can certainly appreciate your position.  My father is also a decorated Vietnam Vet.  Linley, never give up on your father.  Your love, admiration and respect are the greatest gifts you can give him.  When he is ready he will come around.  It takes time, I don't believe anyone can go to Vietnam and come home the same.  I love and deeply respect my father, but it took me years of talking and listening about anything he wanted to talk about to even begin to try to understand what he went through.  I'm 23 years old and understanding the war has been a passion within me since I was very young.  My advice to you right now at this moment, is to learn as much as possible about the war and what soldiers like our fathers went through.  Read as much as possible, talk to other vets (there are some decent friendly folks right here), do what ever you can to learn about Vietnam.  By learning the details of the war, it makes it easier to understand your father just a little bit better, and perhaps make things a little more clear.  I don't pretend to understand all the things that made Vietnam what it was and how it changed people, but learning about it gave me a better understanding, a common place where I could talk to my Dad and see what he experienced just a little bit better (an attempt to visualize it in my mind)  If you can bring yourself, go to the Veteran's Memorial in Washington and just witness the whole experiene.  I was able to understand the emotions of the war better after going   Just face the fact that there are feelings and experiences that are kept close and maybe never shared, but there are feelings and memories that are shared.  Their value is great, no matter how small the memory or experience shared.  Good luck to you!!!<br><br>
   
